 Koninkrijk","England":"England","Ollerton Hall, Cheshire, England":"Ollerton, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ollerton, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1478–1500":"1478–1500","1474–1540":"1474–1540","1495–1540":"1495–1540","1497–Male":"1497–Deceased","1446–1497":"1446–1497","1443–1484":"1443–1484","1446":"1446","1478":"1478","ABT 1494":"about 1494","1500":"1500","1443":"1443","1497":"1497","1540":"1540","1474":"1474","1484":"1484","1495":"1495","about 1497":"about 1497","13 July 1497":"13 July 1497","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Ollerton, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Ollerton Hall, Cheshire, England":"Ollerton, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Ollerton, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Bury in Lancashire (now part of Greater Manchester), or from some other similarly named place. The placename comes from the dative case, <i>byrig</i>, of Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’.","Walloon and French: habitational name from any of several places so named, in Wallonia (Belgium) and Oise (France). The placename is from <i>Buriacum</i>, the name of a Gallo-Roman estate, composed of the personal name <i>Burius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","South German: variant of   Buri  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Buri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Markus, Kurt.","Swiss German and South German: from an Alemannic pet form of the personal name <i>Burkhard</i> (see   Burkhart  ).","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Buro  ."]},{"name":"Burgh","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vernon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Vernon in Eure, France, named from the Gaulish element <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + the Gallo-Roman locative suffix <i>-o</i> (genitive <i>-ōnis</i>).","French: habitational name from the same place as in 1 above or from any of several other places in France with the same name and etymology."],"variants":[{"name":"Varnon","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Northamptonshire): variant of   Vernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Bury de Vernon was born in 1478, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, Ralph Vernon, was 33 and her mother, Lady Margaret Dutton, was 36. She married Richard de Baguley about 1494, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1500, in her hometown, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1478–1500":"1478–1500","1474–1540":"1474–1540","1495–1540":"1495–1540","1497–Male":"1497–Surnud","1446–1497":"1446–1497","1443–1484":"1443–1484","1446":"1446","1478":"1478","ABT 1494":"umbes 1494","1500":"1500","1443":"1443","1497":"1497","1540":"1540","1474":"1474","1484":"1484","1495":"1495","about 1497":"umbes 1497","13 July 1497":"13. juuli 1497","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Ollerton, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Ollerton Hall, Cheshire, England":"Ollerton, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ollerton, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1478–1500":"1478–1500","1474–1540":"1474–1540","1495–1540":"1495–1540","1497–Male":"1497–Kuollut","1446–1497":"1446–1497","14